reviews.review_text:
The GRATEFUL DEAD "Live On Stage" at the Manhattan Center, New York City, New York, United States of America `

~^|\_@|@_/|^~
~<->/<->\<->~

THANK YOU LEIGH ORF FOR SHARING THIS SHOW WITH US! WE LOVE YOU!!

~Classic 71' Soundboard~

~Classic 71'"Sound"~

5 stars for the mix
5 stars for the recording
5 stars for the performances
5 stars for the transfer.

April 71' GRATEFUL DEAD is some of the best "live shows" in recorded human history. 

If you ain't hip to this period of the GRATEFUL DEAD you should "expose" yourself to it...get all the April 71 shows, I did.

Garcia's guitar sound was never better than April 1971. Here's a chance for you to witness the sound and the magic. 

It's hard to remember and even harder to imagine 1971, but it was nothing like today.

I highly recommend adding this show to your 1971 GRATEFUL DEAD collection. It is a "Must Have" show.

An upbeat, energetic, well rehearsed, fun show from a longtime ago when things were still "young".

I recommend using your EQ during playback of most of the shows on the IA, this one included.

Windows Media Player has a 10 band EQ and SRS WOW effects that enhance the sound.

Solid, "In the Pocket" performances of all our favorite songs from the 71 set list.

Here's one way to dowload this show:

The IA recommends users of Windows XP view this web-page with RealPlayer. 

RealPlayer is a free media player you can download at www.realplayer.com. 

Using RealPlayer to view this webpage, click the VBR M3U link to open the songs in the Playlist. If your Playlist is not open, open it by clicking the Playlist icon at the lower right hand corner of RealPlayer. Once the songs are in the Playlist, double click the song to play it, then click the record button at the lower left hand corner of Realplayer to record it. 

When the red line reaches the other end click the stop button to download the song. Your song is in the RealPlayer Downloads folder. 

Repeat these steps for each song.

Eat, Drink, Be Merry and Listen to the GRATEFUL DEAD.

Thanks for the LOVE from 1971.

PS: Remember to click on the "DeadLists Project" link and get the ticket stub for this show.
thank you i agree with the above review.  a nice, well recorded, up beat concert.  thank you for all your hard work.

Great year for the dead I agree with the poster below 100 percent.  The band was at the top of their game during this period.  The sound was very clean and upbeat.  

Wish I could own this recording on CD.  Or better yet, wish I was there to witness the Dead during this year and '72 as well.  It's clear the early 70's were a good time to be a Deadhead.  

Peace

Good-Time Music I have to concur. April of 1971? How could it be less than five stars? While not as intense (or scary) as '69, neither were our trips.

This has to be the definition of Good-Time Music.
Yes it was a good night ... and the Dead thought so too, since three of the tunes from this concert made their way to the "Skull and Roses" album (Big Railroad Blues, NFA and GDTRFB).
